@node "introduction" "Introduction"
@next "contents"
 This archive contains 5 elegant :) bootpics, 704x566 format, 256 colors,
realized using some nice backgrounds from Scala MM300. The pictures were
originally made to be used with an Amiga with OS and WB 3.0 and running on a
68030 50MHz processor, but I included in this archive many @{"brushes" link "usebrushes" 0} that you
can use to customize the pictures to suit your system, so the "requirements"
are:
 - an Amiga
 - OS and WB 3.0/3.1
 - 68020/030/040/060 processor running at 14/25/28/33/40/50 MHz
 - a simple paint program (e.g. an old version of DPaint) IF you need to
   change the configuration displayed from the default one, but keep in
   mind that the pictures are in GIF format (they take MUCH less space) so
   you may need to convert them before loading them in the paint program
   (DPaint, for example, does not load GIF pictures); this is easily
   achieved with any gfx conversion program you can find on Aminet, like
   "GfxCon".

If you're still looking for a good bootpic viewer, I'd recommend "SysPic", a
fully featured one.
@endnode

@node "contents" "Archive contents"
@next "usebrushes"
 The main directory of this archive contains the pictures:

     AMYintroFabric.gif
     AMYintroFlowers.gif
     AMYintroGrass.gif
     AMYintroStone.gif
     AMYintroWater.gif

Then there's the "Brushes" sub-directory, which contains 5 other
sub-directories, each one dedicated to one of the pictures; so the "Fabric"
directory contains the @{"brushes" link "usebrushes" 0} to be used with the "AMYintroFabric" picture,
and so on... Inside each one of these sub-directories you will find 10
@{"brushes" link "usebrushes" 0}:

     1 for changing the OS version from 3.0 to 3.1:
       ".....OS31_br.iff"

     1 for changing the WB version from 3.0 to 3.1:
       ".....WB31_br.iff"

     3 for changing the processor model:
       ".....020_br.iff"
       ".....040_br.iff"
       ".....060_br.iff"

     5 for changing the processor speed:
       ".....14MHz_br.iff"
       ".....25MHz_br.iff"
       ".....28MHz_br.iff"
       ".....30MHz_br.iff"
       ".....40MHz_br.iff"

I hope I have not left out any important processor/speed (I suppose there's
not many of you having a 68010 installed). Make me know if you find any "bug"
:) (that is: missing pieces) or if you have some particular need.
@endnode

@node "usebrushes" "Using the brushes"
@next "author"
 Placing the brushes in the right place requires some precision work, but I'm
sure that most of you will not experience any problem; just load your
favourite paint program (remember, you must have the pictures in a suitable
format for your program), load in the picture, load the brush and put it in
the right place.

However, I tried to make your work easier than it could have been: I cut the
brushes in a way that I captured the first "bright" pixels of the nearest
characters. Let me better explain this concept: if you take a look at any of
the "OS31" brushes, you will notice some bright pixels on the left, those
pixels belong to the "S" of "AmigaOS"; actually, they form the rightmost
column of bright pixels (that is: excluding shadows and smoothed pixels) of
the "S"; so they make up for a good reference point when you have to put the
"3.1" in the right place: just place it in a way that the "S" doesn't look
distorted or that you don't see any floating bright pixels between the "S" and
the "3.1". The same goes for the "WB31" brushes: in this case you'll see the
rightmost pixels of the "h" making their appearance on the left edge of the
brush.

About the other brushes, the trick is very similar, it's just that this time
you have TWO reference points: the character to the left and the one to the
right. So in the "processor model" brushes you'll see the rightmost pixels of
the "0" (third digit from the right in the "680x0") and the leftmost pixels of
the "/" (sometimes I just cut the relevant digit - "2", "4" or "6" - to make
the file smaller; in these cases, the pixels on the right of the brush come
out of the last "0" in "680x0"), while in the "speed" brushes you'll find the
rightmost pixels of the "/" and the leftmost pixels of the "M" in "MHz".

Ehm... it seems I'm not so good at explaining things, I hope I've not confused
you, just try and you'll see how easy it really is! ;^)
@endnode

